[Althouth the above report is a warning, rather than a case report, it is timely, as the season for tick activity is just now beginning in the northeastern USA. There is no commercially available vaccine for Powassan virus. The best way to prevent infection is to avoid tick bites. The tick involved in the 2016 cases was not identified, but may have been the black-legged tick _Ixodes scapulars_.

The USA CDC notes: "Human Powassan (POW) virus infections have been recognized in the United States, Canada and Russia. In the United States, cases of POW virus disease have been reported primarily from northeastern states and the Great Lakes region. These cases occur primarily in the late spring, early summer and mid-fall when ticks are most active. POW virus disease cases are rare but the reported number of cases has increased in recent years. All residents of and visitors to areas where POW virus activity has been identified are at risk of infection. People who engage in outdoor work and recreational activities in endemic areas are at increased risk of infection" (http://www.cdc.gov/powassan/statistics.html). - Mod.TY

